    <text>
        <body><div type="bibliography">
                
            <p>Not published before <bibl><ptr target="#IGCyr"/> <citedRange>121700</citedRange></bibl>.</p>
            <p>Cf. <bibl><ptr target="#belzic2022"/>, catalogue <citedRange>B.87</citedRange></bibl>.</p>
            </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><persName type="attested" key=""><name nymRef="#Στρατώι"><supplied reason="lost" cert="low">Στρα</supplied>τὼι</name> 
                        <persName type="attested" key=""><name nymRef="#Εὐπόλεμος" type="patronymic">Εὐπολέμω</name></persName></persName>
	 </ab>
            </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p/>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="fr" xml:space="preserve">
            <p><supplied reason="lost" cert="low">Stra</supplied>tô fille d'Eupolémos.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="en" xml:space="preserve">
            <p><supplied reason="lost" cert="low">Stra</supplied>to daughter of Eupolemos.</p>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="it" xml:space="preserve">
            <p><supplied reason="lost" cert="low">Stra</supplied>tò figlia di Eupolemos.</p>
         </div><div type="commentary">
                
               <p>A man named Eupolemos was the father of two soldiers mentionned in <ref type="inscription" source="#IGCyr2">IGCyr015100</ref> (l.10 and l.11). 
               This woman might be his daughter. Her name cannot be restored with full confidence: we prefer <foreign xml:lang="grc">Στρατώι</foreign>, which is the only one matching 
                   the gap which is attested up to now in Cyrenaica for the Hellenistic period  (see <ref type="inscription" source="#IGCyr2">IGCyr105600</ref>). However, <foreign xml:lang="grc">Μυρτώι</foreign>, known in the first century AD would also fit the presumable gap, as well as <foreign xml:lang="grc">Κρατώι</foreign>, 
                   attested at Cos in the first century BC.</p>
	<p/>
	<p/>
            </div></body>
